        "excerpt": "The LORD also has a dispute with Judah, and will punish Jacob according to his ways; he will repay him according to his deeds.",
        "body": "Verse 2 establishes the legal framework for the entire chapter. The word *riv* is not a general expression of divine displeasure but a technical term from covenant-treaty law — the suzerain's formal legal complaint against a vassal who has broken the treaty terms. The use of *riv* activates the entire legal-prophetic tradition: Micah 6:1-2 uses it for the same covenant lawsuit format; Isaiah 1:18 opens a similar proceeding. The judgment will be calibrated precisely to 'his ways' and 'his deeds' — this is not arbitrary punishment but a covenantal accounting.\n\nVerse 2's inclusion of Judah ('the LORD also has a dispute with Judah') is significant. Up to this point in Hosea, Judah has occasionally appeared as a positive contrast to Ephraim (cf. 1:7; 4:15). Here, both kingdoms stand under the same lawsuit. The 'also' (*gam*) refuses to allow the southern kingdom any self-congratulatory exemption. Applied canonically, this move is consistent with Paul's argument in Romans 3:9-19: both Jew and Gentile, both northern and southern kingdom, fall under the same divine verdict.\n\nThe pivot to Jacob in verses 3-5 is a masterwork of typological argument. Hosea reaches behind the current generation — behind the monarchy, behind the conquest, behind even the exodus — to the patriarch in the womb. 'In the womb he took his brother by the heel' (12:3; Genesis 25:26). The name 'Jacob' (*yaaqov*) puns on 'heel' (*aqev*) — the man's name encodes his first act of grasping. Hosea is saying: what Ephraim is doing now with dishonest scales and wind-chasing alliances is the same character in a different key.\n\nBut the Jacob biography does not end at deception. Verse 4 records the turn: 'he wrestled with the angel and prevailed; he wept and sought His favor.' The weeping is the chapter's most theologically freighted detail. The man who had been grasping his brother's heel in the womb, deceiving his father for a blessing, running from Esau, outwitting Laban — this same man, at Penuel, when he could no longer maneuver, wept. And found God at Bethel. The structural implication for the chapter is precise: the same character that produced Ephraim's current apostasy also produced Jacob's repentance. The ancestors' cure is available to the descendants.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Riv* (dispute, lawsuit) — a forensic term for the covenant lawsuit genre. *Sarah* (wrestled/contended, 12:3) is the verbal root behind the name 'Israel' (*yisrael* — 'he strives with God'). *Maleakh* (angel) in verse 4 — the same figure Jacob encounters at Penuel (Genesis 32:24-32), identified in Hosea's text as God Himself speaking at Bethel (12:4b-5), suggesting the pre-incarnate Angel of the LORD."
