        "number": 3,
        "title": "Therefore return — the chapter's central imperative",
        "range": "12:6",
        "excerpt": "Therefore, return to your God, observe kindness and justice, and wait for your God continually.",
        "body": "Verse 6 is the chapter's structural and theological center, and it stands as its only affirmative command. The *therefore* (*ve-attah*) anchors the imperative in what has just been established: because the LORD God of hosts (12:5) is who He is, and because He met even the heel-grasping, deceptive, fleeing Jacob when Jacob finally wept and sought Him (12:4), there is a basis — a historically demonstrated basis — for Ephraim to return. The imperative is not a demand made in a vacuum but an invitation grounded in demonstrated covenant faithfulness.\n\nThe command has three dimensions that together constitute a complete picture of covenant return. First, *return to your God* — the verb *shuv* is the Old Testament's most comprehensive word for repentance. It is not merely emotional remorse but a turning of the whole person, a reversal of direction. What Ephraim must turn from is named in verse 1: wind-chasing, lie-multiplying, Assyrian covenants, Egyptian tribute. Second, *observe chesed and justice* — *chesed* is the covenant-loyalty word, the steadfast love that God embodies and that His people are called to embody toward one another. *Mishpat* is justice, the right ordering of social relations. Together they are the moral content of covenant life (cf. Micah 6:8; Hosea 6:6). Third, *wait for your God continually* — the word *qavah* carries the sense of active, expectant orientation toward God. It is the opposite of the frantic pursuit of verse 1. To 'wait continually' is to reorient the national life from the frantic seeking of political solutions to a posture of confident dependence on the covenant God.\n\nThe three-part structure of the imperative — return (direction), observe chesed and justice (conduct), wait (posture) — anticipates the New Testament's pattern of repentance as comprehensive: a turning of the will, a transformation of behavior, and a sustained orientation of trust. Tim Keller, commenting on the prophetic call to return, notes that the prophets are not calling for behavioral adjustment but for a fundamental reordering of what the community trusts and loves.\n\nThat verse 6 is immediately followed by renewed accusation (12:7ff) rather than a description of Israel's response gives it a haunting quality — the invitation stands open, unanswered, surrounded by evidence that the nation has refused it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shuv* (return) is the OT's master-word for repentance — appearing over 1,000 times in the Hebrew Bible, consistently carrying the sense of a directional reversal of the whole person, not merely emotional contrition. *Chesed* (kindness/lovingkindness) is the covenant-loyalty word, capturing both the relational warmth and the legal faithfulness of covenant life. *Qavah* (wait/hope) — to bind oneself to, to expect; the same root as the 'cord' (*tikvah*) of Joshua 2:18 — Rahab's crimson thread of hope."
